Amazon Route 53 is AWS’s highly available and scalable Domain Name System (DNS) web service. It’s designed to route end-user requests to applications running on AWS or elsewhere, with features that go beyond traditional DNS.

Key Features
Domain Registration: Register new domain names directly in Route 53.
DNS Service: Host DNS zones and manage records (A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, TXT, etc.).
Traffic Routing Policies:
Simple Routing: Directs traffic to a single resource.
Weighted Routing: Distributes traffic based on percentages (great for A/B testing).
Latency-Based Routing: Sends users to the region with the lowest latency.
Geolocation Routing: Routes based on user’s geographic location.
Failover Routing: Provides high availability by redirecting traffic if a resource fails.
Health Checks & Monitoring: Automatically reroutes traffic away from unhealthy endpoints.
Integration with AWS Services: Works seamlessly with CloudFront, S3, EC2, ELB, and more.

Use Cases
Website Hosting: Manage DNS for websites hosted on AWS or external servers.
Global Applications: Use latency-based routing to improve performance for worldwide users.
Disaster Recovery: Failover routing ensures continuity during outages.
Hybrid Cloud: Route traffic between AWS and on-premises environments.
